The stuff described on the first part of that page has been supported by GCC for ages. It's useful where structs and unions are deeply nested, e.g.:<p><pre><code>  enum MyStructType { MyInt, MyFloat };
  struct my_struct
  {
    enum MyStructType type;
    union
    {
      struct {
        int my_int;
      } as_int;
      struct {
        float my_float;
      } as_float;
    } d;
  };
</code></pre>
To get to the actual data, in standard C89/99 you need to do this:<p><pre><code>  struct my_struct* s = /* ... */;
  if (s->type == MyInt)
    printf("%i
", s->d.as_int.my_int); /* <- !!!!!! */
  else
    printf("%f
", s->d.as_float.my_float); /* <- !!!!!! */
</code></pre>
With the extension, the inner union and struct members are added to the outer struct/union's namespace:<p><pre><code>  enum MyStructType { MyInt, MyFloat };
  struct my_struct
  {
    enum MyStructType type;
    union
    {
      struct {
        int my_int;
      };
      struct {
        float my_float;
      };
    }; /* note: no name */
  };
</code></pre>
Now the access code is much nicer:<p><pre><code>  struct my_struct* s = /* ... */;
  if (s->type == MyInt)
    printf("%i
", s->my_int);  /* <- !!!!!! */
  else
    printf("%f
", s->my_float);  /* <- !!!!!! */

</code></pre>
The second part extends this to typedefs, while the third part, the Plan9 addition (which is presumably the reason for the HN submission) gives you an implicit struct pointer conversion for structs composed of other structs, a bit like C++'s implicit pointer conversion for <i>inheritance</i>. The page has an example of this already:<p><pre><code>  struct s1 { int a; };
  struct s2 { struct s1; };
  extern void f1 (struct s1 *);
  void f2 (struct s2 *p) { f1 (p); }
</code></pre>
This is how you'd normally have to do it:<p><pre><code>  struct s1 { int a; };
  struct s2 { struct s1 my_s1; }; // <- note non-anonymous struct field
  extern void f1 (struct s1 *);
  void f2 (struct s2 *p) { f1 (&p->my_s1); } // <- my code is always littered with this idiom

</code></pre>
All of this might not seem like much, but complicated data structures really aren't a forte of the C syntax. A bit of sugar alleviates at least some of the endless repetition.

The last part is pretty cool (the first bit has been supported by GCC for years), though it would be even more helpful to be able to do the reverse concisely - convert a pointer to the contained struct to a pointer to the containing one. In my C code I invariably use (something similar to) the container_of() macro used in the Linux kernel [1]. The primary use is in callbacks associated with a particular object that can be embedded in larger structures.<p>Right now, say a library I'm using exposes this:<p><pre><code>  struct lib_struct {
    int foo;
    char* bar;
  };
  typedef void (*lib_callback)(struct lib_struct*);
  extern void lib_fn(struct lib_struct* obj, lib_callback cb);
</code></pre>
If I want to use that in one of my own data structures:<p><pre><code>  struct my_struct {
    struct lib_struct lib_st;
    int my_own_data;
  };

  static void my_callback(struct lib_struct* lib_st)
  {
    // plan9 extension does not appear to help here...
    struct my_struct* me = container_of(lib_st, struct my_struct, lib_st);
    printf("%i
", me->my_own_data);
  }

    /* elsewhere... */
    struct my_struct* m = /* ... */;
    // ... though it would here:
    lib_fn(&m->lib_st, my_callback);
</code></pre>
It'd be handy to be able to condense the container_of line somewhat, while maintaining (some) type safety.<p>[1] <a href="http://www.kroah.com/log/linux/container_of.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.kroah.com/log/linux/container_of.html</a> - I use a similar macro that preserves NULL pointers.
